Collapse over non-independent rows

When two or more rows contain data from the same infants, those are no longer independent. To make up for this, we take the median (which if there are 2 rows defaults to the average) effect size. Note that analyses based on t-values (see replicability analyses) should check whether this way we lose significant t-values.

The Meta-analysis

Starting with Direct Replications

We defined a direct replication as any study that used a continuous stream that could only be segmented via transitional probabilities (i.e. no other cue either in tandem with or in contrast to TPs), and where there was no fundamental change to the experimental protocol. For example, experiments that consist of a priming period prior to familiarization were not included as direct replications, nor were experiments that invovled a test using novel tokens or sentence frames, rather than test items extracted directly from the speech stream.

#### Create subsets ####

# direct replications only, as coded in the spreadsheet

db_DR <- db %>% filter(DirectRep == "yes")
#### Random effect model direct replications ####

rma_DR <- rma.mv(g_calc, g_var_calc, data = db_DR, random = ~1 | short_cite)

summary(rma_DR)

Plots

+ Forest

#forest(rma_DR)

##Borrowing some code to make this a ggplot: 
#https://sakaluk.wordpress.com/2016/02/16/7-make-it-pretty-plots-for-met#a-analysis/

#Rename a bunch of things for ease
dat=db_DR
dat <-
  dat %>% 
  rename(cite = short_cite,
         yi = g_calc,
         vi = g_var_calc)

#Reorder bibliographic info based on value of g (yi), so effect sizes can be plotted in descending order

dat <-
  dat %>% 
  select(cite, expt_num, same_infant, mean_age_1, yi, vi) %>% 
  mutate(study_ref = paste(cite, expt_num, same_infant, sep=',')) %>% 
  arrange(desc(yi))

#Get standard errors from variances
dat$se = sqrt(dat$vi)

#Calculate 95% CI values
dat$lowerci = (-1.96*dat$se)+dat$yi
dat$upperci = (1.96*dat$se)+dat$yi

#Themes and plot
apatheme=theme_bw()+
  theme(#panel.grid.major=element_blank(),
        #panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),
        #panel.border=element_blank(),
        axis.line=element_line(),
        text=element_text(family='Times'),
        legend.position='none')
p=
  ggplot(dat, aes(y=reorder(study_ref, -yi), x=yi, xmin=lowerci, xmax=upperci))+
  #Add data points and color them black
  geom_point(color = 'black')+
  #Add 'special' points for the summary estimates, by making them diamond shaped
#  geom_point(data=subset(dat, tester=='Summary'), color='black', shape=18, size=4)+
  #add the CI error bars
  geom_errorbarh(height=.1)+
  #Specify the limits of the x-axis and relabel it to something more meaningful
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-1.5,1.5), name='Standardized Mean Difference (g)')+
  #Give y-axis a meaningful label
  ylab('Reference')+
  #Add a vertical dashed line indicating an effect size of zero, for reference
  geom_vline(xintercept=0, color='grey', linetype='dashed')+
  #Add a vertical line to show mean effect
  geom_vline(xintercept=0.19, color='black', linetype='dashed')+
  #Create sub-plots (i.e., facets) based on levels of setting
  #And allow them to have their own unique axes (so authors don't redundantly repeat)
  #facet_grid(setting~., scales= 'free', space='free')+
  #Apply my APA theme
  apatheme

p

ggsave("figures/ForestPlot_DR.png", p)

+ Funnel

### This code is from:
### https://sakaluk.wordpress.com/2016/02/16/7-make-it-pretty-plots-for-met#a-analysis/
### Store the meta-analytic estimate and its standard error from whatever
### model you run (substitute your own values) rma_DR
estimate = 0.2055
se = 0.0965

# Store a vector of values that spans the range from 0 to the max value of
# impression (standard error) in your dataset. Make the increment (the final
# value) small enough (I choose 0.001) to ensure your whole range of data is
# captured
se.seq = seq(0, max(dat$se), 0.001)

# Now, compute vectors of the lower-limit and upper limit values for the 95%
# CI region, using the range of SE that you generated in the previous step,
# and the stored value of your meta-analytic estimate.
ll95 = estimate - (1.96 * se.seq)
ul95 = estimate + (1.96 * se.seq)

# You can do this for a 99% CI region too
ll99 = estimate - (3.29 * se.seq)
ul99 = estimate + (3.29 * se.seq)

# And finally, do the same thing except now calculating the confidence
# interval for your meta-analytic estimate based on the stored value of its
# standard error
meanll95 = estimate - (1.96 * se)
meanul95 = estimate + (1.96 * se)

# Now, smash all of those calculated values into one data frame (called
# 'dfCI'). You might get a warning about '...row names were found from a
# short variable...' You can ignore it.
dfCI = data.frame(ll95, ul95, ll99, ul99, se.seq, estimate, meanll95, meanul95)

# Now we can actually make the funnel plot. Using your original data-frame,
# map standard error to your x-axis (for now) and Zr to your y-axis
fp = ggplot(aes(x = se, y = yi), data = dat) + # Regression line for the FP asymmetry
geom_smooth(aes(x = se, y = yi), method = "lm", colour = "darkgrey", alpha = 0.5, 
    se = FALSE, data = dat) + # Add your data-points to the scatterplot
geom_point(size = 2.5, colour = "black") + # Give the x- and y- axes informative labels
xlab("Standard Error") + ylab("Hedge's g") + # Now using the 'dfCI' data-frame we created, plot dotted lines
# corresponding to the lower and upper limits of your 95% CI region And
# dashed lines corresponding to your 99% CI region Add lines corresponding
# to 0 and estimate
geom_line(aes(x = se.seq, y = 0), linetype = "solid", data = dfCI) + geom_line(aes(x = se.seq, 
    y = estimate), linetype = "dashed", data = dfCI) + geom_line(aes(x = se.seq, 
    y = ll95), linetype = "dotted", data = dfCI) + geom_line(aes(x = se.seq, 
    y = ul95), linetype = "dotted", data = dfCI) + # geom_line(aes(x = se.seq, y = ll99), linetype = 'dashed', data = dfCI) +
# geom_line(aes(x = se.seq, y = ul99), linetype = 'dashed', data = dfCI) +
# Now plot dotted lines corresponding to the 95% CI of your meta-analytic
# estimate geom_segment(aes(x = min(se.seq), y = meanll95, xend =
# max(se.seq), yend = meanll95), linetype='dotted', data=dfCI) +
# geom_segment(aes(x = min(se.seq), y = meanul95, xend = max(se.seq), yend =
# meanul95), linetype='dotted', data=dfCI) + Reverse the x-axis ordering
# (se) so that the tip of the funnel will appear at the top of the figure
# once we swap the x- and y-axes...
scale_x_reverse() + # Specify the range and interval for the tick-marks of the y-axis (Zr);
# Choose values that work for you based on your data
scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-0.45, 0.8, 0.25)) + # And now we flip the axes so that SE is on y- and Zr is on x-
coord_flip() + # Finally, apply my APA-format theme (see code at end of post). You could,
# alternatively, specify theme_bw() instead.
apatheme

# Call the pretty funnel plot
fp

ggsave("figures/FunnelPlot_DR.pdf")

Additional cues

This requires a second thought. There are multiple experiments here that are intentionally testing whether additional cues supercede SL. This has been coded in two ways: cues that interfere with the TP structure, and cues that interfere with the Native language expectations. In many cases these will be the same (i.e. iambic stress interferes with the TP structure because it contradicts native language expectations).

For clarity, we focus for now on TP cue conflicts.

# Look at additional cues
rma_cue = rma.mv(g_calc, g_var_calc, mods = ~factor(cue_conflict_TP), data = db, 
    random = ~1 | short_cite)
summary(rma_cue)

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
dat <- db %>% rename(cite = short_cite, yi = g_calc, vi = g_var_calc) %>% mutate(study_ref = paste(cite, 
    expt_num, same_infant, sep = ",")) %>% filter(cue_conflict_TP != "")
dat$se = sqrt(dat$vi)
dat$lowerci = (-1.96 * dat$se) + dat$yi
dat$upperci = (1.96 * dat$se) + dat$yi

ggplot(dat, aes(y = reorder(study_ref, -yi), x = yi, xmin = lowerci, xmax = upperci)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = cue_conflict_TP)) + geom_errorbarh(height = 0.1) + 
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1.5, 1.5), name = "Standardized Mean Difference (g)") + 
    ylab("Reference") + geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "grey", linetype = "dashed") + 
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0.31, color = "black", linetype = "dashed")
